# VK Bot project — external references

## VK API and bot changes

When editing or extending this VK bot (callbacks, messages, groups, tokens, limits, payloads, keyboards, etc.), **consult the official VK developer documentation** and align behavior with it:

- [VK for developers — documentation guide](https://dev.vk.com/ru/guide)

Prefer citing or following that documentation over assumptions when API behavior, parameters, or platform rules matter.

## Site integration — tournament.pavelsolntsev.ru

If the bot or this repo **interacts with** [https://tournament.pavelsolntsev.ru/](https://tournament.pavelsolntsev.ru/) (scraping, API calls, URLs, data shapes, auth, or shared business rules), **also inspect the local codebase** at:

`D:\web\football`

Use that project as the source of truth for how the site works, endpoints, models, and conventions unless this repo explicitly duplicates them.

## Telegram parity — reference implementation

If a task is related to implementation or behavior analogous to Telegram, use solutions from this repository as the primary reference during search and analysis:

- [pavelsolnsev/telegram-bot](https://github.com/pavelsolnsev/telegram-bot)

## Buttons and text commands — same behavior

When the bot exposes **the same user action** through more than one entry point (for example a **keyboard / callback button** and a **text command**, or payload vs typed command), **implement the full behavior for every path**:

- **Do not** ship logic only on the button or only on the command while the other path is missing, stubbed, or divergent.
- Prefer **one shared handler or function** for the core behavior, and call it from both the callback/button path and the command/message path so fixes and edge cases stay in sync.

If a path is intentionally unsupported, document why in code (brief comment) near the entry points; otherwise assume both must work the same way.
